nlohmann::json& resources = aResp->res.jsonValue["Links"][resource];
resources = nlohmann::json::array();

That ensures that when the collection is empty, we get an empty array properly.

I spent some time trying to mock out the bus for `sdbusplus::asio::getProperty`, but it seems like `crow::connections::systemBus`.

I was trying to mock it with
```
    sdbusplus::SdBusMock mock;
    sdbusplus::bus_t bus = sdbusplus::get_mocked_new(&mock);
    crow::connections::systemBus =
        reinterpret_cast<sdbusplus::asio::connection*>(&bus);
```

But it seems like it is using the lower level `sd_bus` instead of `sdbusplus::bus_t` that we are mocking.
```
connection(boost::asio::io_context& io, sd_bus* bus) :
        sdbusplus::bus_t(bus), io_(io), socket(io_)
    {
        socket.assign(get_fd());
        read_wait();
    }
```

So I am not too sure how to test this properly.

I converted into synchronous call and was able test it, but the async one with `getProperty` failed.

we're not very consistent in this regard, but generally for the things we support we tend to do what will has done here, and expose the tree links regardless, and in the case where there are no devices, we have an empty array.

With that said, I do think you're right, we should do something like

nlohmann::json::array_t storages;

for (....){
...
storages.push_back(...)
}

asyncResp->res.jsonValue["Links"]["Storage@odata.count"] = storages.size();
asyncResp->res.jsonValue["Links"]["Storage"] = std::move(storages);
